{"Body": "<p>Political party &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; have been refused recognition as a society. This refusal was made on the grounds that the Central Societies Committee executive felt that &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; did not meet their criteria for establishing a society. CSC also felt that the aims of the organisation were already covered by existing societies.</p>\n<p>&Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; are a socialist republican party that, according to their website, are, &ldquo;committed to ending the British occupation of the six counties and the establishment of a thirty-two county Democratic Socialist Republic.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>&Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; have stated that they wish to appeal the decision but have yet to officially begin the process with CSC. It has been stated by the CSC executive that &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; TCD would not contribute to college life.</p>\n<p>A petition was established to recognise &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; as a student society. It received over 100 names and student IDs. According to a press release from Trinity &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; the organisation plans to bring up the matter of their recognition at the CSC&rsquo;s Term General Meeting this coming January, though to do this they will need support from the treasurers of two existing, fully recognised societies.</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>Political party &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; have been refused recognition as a society. This refusal was made on the grounds that the Central Societies Committee executive felt that &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; did not meet their criteria for establishing a society. CSC also felt that the aims of the organisation were already covered by existing societies.</p>\n<p>&Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; are a socialist republican party that, according to their website, are, &ldquo;committed to ending the British occupation of the six counties and the establishment of a thirty-two county Democratic Socialist Republic.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>&Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; have stated that they wish to appeal the decision but have yet to officially begin the process with CSC. It has been stated by the CSC executive that &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; TCD would not contribute to college life.</p>\n<p>A petition was established to recognise &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; as a student society. It received over 100 names and student IDs. According to a press release from Trinity &Eacute;ir&iacute;g&iacute; the organisation plans to bring up the matter of their recognition at the CSC&rsquo;s Term General Meeting this coming January, though to do this they will need support from the treasurers of two existing, fully recognised societies.</p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "18104", "Heading": "Republicans &#201;ir&#237;g&#237; denied society status"}